  "Q'ero/Quechua":       '#2a5a85',  // Andean blue
  'Inca':                '#b8252b',  // Mascaipacha scarlet — the imperial fringe of the Sapa Inca's royal llautu (headband), the most-restricted color in the Inca state, woven from vicuña wool dyed with cochineal-and-achiote, worn only by the reigning emperor; the visual signature of the Tahuantinsuyu state, attested in Cieza de León (1553) and Garcilaso (1609) and on textile fragments from the imperial-period Cuzco region
  'Manipuri':            '#4a4a8a',  // Phanek-Mayek-Naibi indigo — the deep blue-purple stripe of the foundational Meitei phanek (traditional wraparound skirt), woven on the lai-haraoba ritual loom; the indigo-on-white pattern preserves continuous Meitei textile-cultural-identity from at least the medieval Manipuri kingdom (1110 CE Loiyumba Shilyel record) through the modern era
  'Tagalog':             '#7a8aa0',  // Pre-colonial Tagalog warrior-tattoo blue-gray — the foundational pre-Hispanic Filipino body-modification color (referenced as "Pintados" in Spanish 1565+ accounts), produced from boiled-soot-and-sugarcane-juice tattoo ink applied to chest, back, and limbs of datu-class warriors as both rank-marker and protective-magic; the iconographic anchor of pre-colonial Tagalog material-cultural identity
  'Suludnon':            '#6a3a48',  // Panay-Bukidnon panubok crimson — the foundational Suludnon embroidery red used in panubok ceremonial-cloth attached to the hablon-weave, central to the Hinilawod oral-epic performance tradition; produced from sappanwood (Caesalpinia sappan) bark dye in the highland Panay-Bukidnon textile complex documented by F. Landa Jocano (1968) and the Patubas dictionary tradition
