      sources: [
        { claim: 'existence', citations: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Táin Bó Fraích (Old Irish, 8th-9th c. — the eponymous saga, the major source); Táin Bó Cúailnge (LU recension late 11th c., LL recension 12th c. — the death-at-ford episode); Acallam na Senórach (12th c.); Lebor Gabála Érenn (genealogical tract)' }], weight: 'primary' },
        { claim: 'parentage', citations: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Táin Bó Fraích §1' }], weight: 'primary' },
      ],
      notes: 'Half-divine son of the Tuatha Dé Danann figure Bé Find (sister of Boann) by the mortal Connacht prince Idath. The eponymous hero of Táin Bó Fraích — one of the remscéla (preliminary tales) of the Táin Bó Cúailnge cycle. "Most beautiful of the warriors of Ireland" per the saga-formula; the otherworldly endowments his Tuatha Dé Danann mother provides (garments, healing-care after the serpent-fight) mark the maternal-divine-line throughout the saga. Killed by Cú Chulainn at a ford during the Táin Bó Cúailnge — the cross-saga death-link that places Fráech in the Ulster-cycle world. Father Idath left unseeded — appears only as a name in the saga-opening.',
