      sources: [
        { claim: 'existence', citations: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Mutsu Waki (Tale of Mutsu, c. 1062 — contemporary Japanese chronicle); Ōshū Gosannenki (chronicle of the Later Three-Years War, c. 1170); Heike Monogatari book 11 (Tale of the Heike, early 13th c.); Konjaku Monogatari shū book 25 tale 13; Sonpi Bunmyaku (genealogical compilation); contemporary court diaries' }], weight: 'primary' },
        { claim: 'parentage', citations: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Heike Monogatari book 11 (medieval-literary divine-paternity claim); Mutsu Waki (genpuku-naming as Hachiman Tarō)' }], weight: 'primary', notes: 'Mongán-pattern: historical samurai with medieval-literary divine-paternity claim (~130 years after death) from contemporaneous court literature. Biological father Yoriyoshi encoded as social-father; divine paternity Hachiman encoded as primary parentage per the Mongán-precedent in the registry.' },
      ],
      notes: 'Half-divine son of Hachiman under the Mongán-pattern medieval-literary divine-paternity claim. Historical samurai (1039-1106 CE), distinguished commander in the Former Nine-Years and Later Three-Years Wars. The Hachimantarō naming at his genpuku ceremony at Iwashimizu Hachimangū, the father-Yoriyoshi dream of Hachiman granting the sword, and the Heike Monogatari\'s explicit "son or avatar of Hachiman" attribution constitute the medieval-literary divine-paternity tradition. Posthumously elevated to kami status by the Minamoto clan as their patron ancestral kami; the Hachiman-Minamoto-tutelary relationship Yoshiie cemented became the religious foundation of the Kamakura shogunate founded by his great-grandson Yoritomo. Biological father Minamoto no Yoriyoshi encoded as social-father; the divine-paternity tradition is the operative parentage under the registry\'s strict-criterion-with-Mongán-pattern philosophy.',
