    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    //  CHINESE (deepening) — Jade Emperor + Three Sovereigns Five Emperors +
    //  Xia foundation
    //  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    //  Adds the canonical Chinese mytho-historical dynastic backbone to the
    //  existing Yaoji/Erlang-Shen Bao Lian Deng cluster. The Three Sovereigns
    //  Five Emperors (San Huang Wu Di) lineage from Huangdi (Yellow Emperor)
    //  through Yao and Shun to Yu the Great and the foundation of the Xia
    //  dynasty (traditional 2070 BCE) constitutes the foundational pre-
    //  dynastic sovereign-genealogical framework of Chinese civilization,
    //  preserved primarily in Sima Qian\'s Shiji (Records of the Grand
    //  Historian, c. 91 BCE) and supplemented by the Shanhaijing (Classic
    //  of Mountains and Seas), the Bamboo Annals (Zhushu Jinian), and
    //  later compilations.
    //
    //  Strict-pass treatment: The Han-period Shiji "rationalized" reading of
    //  the lineage — in which figures like Huangdi, Yao, Shun, Yu have
    //  named mortal parents (Shaodian/Fubao for Huangdi; Diku for Yao;
    //  Gusou/Wo Deng for Shun; Gun for Yu) — produces strict-pass-clean
    //  mortal-class entries. Older oral-mythological strata in which these
    //  figures are conceived through divine-light, footprint-stepping, or
    //  rainbow-encounter (preserved in the Da Dai Liji, the Lushi Chunqiu,
    //  and various Han-period commentaries) would block several from strict-
    //  pass; the registry adopts the orthodox-Shiji reading. The genealogical
    //  chain Huangdi + Leizu → Changyi → Zhuanxu and Gun → Yu → Qi
    //  constitute the registered parent-child links; isolated entries with
    //  empty parentIds (Diku, Yao, Shun, Gun) reflect the absence of the
    //  intermediate-generation registered ancestors and document the
    //  Shiji-attested chain in entry notes.
    //
    //  Pantheon-tier additions: Yu Huang Da Di (Jade Emperor), supreme
    //  heaven-deity of the folk-Daoist pantheon; Xiwangmu (Queen Mother of
    //  the West), the goddess of Mount Kunlun and immortality. Both
    //  parentIds=[] per pantheon-deity convention.
    //
    //  Sources: Sima Qian, Shiji / Records of the Grand Historian (c. 91
    //  BCE) Chs. 1-2 (Wudi Benji "Annals of the Five Emperors") and Ch. 2
    //  (Xia Benji "Annals of Xia"); Burton Watson trans., Records of the
    //  Grand Historian: Han Dynasty (1993, Columbia). Shanhaijing / Classic
    //  of Mountains and Seas (compiled 4th c. BCE-1st c. CE; Strassberg
    //  trans. 2002). Zhushu Jinian / Bamboo Annals (4th c. BCE compilation,
    //  rediscovered 281 CE). Da Dai Liji (Records of Ritual Compiled by
    //  Dai the Elder, Han period). For Daoist-pantheon material: Livia
    //  Kohn, ed., Daoism Handbook (2000); Suzanne Cahill, Transcendence
    //  and Divine Passion: The Queen Mother of the West in Medieval China
    //  (1993). For modern critical-historical assessment of the Three-
    //  Sovereigns-Five-Emperors framework: K. C. Chang, Art, Myth, and
    //  Ritual: The Path to Political Authority in Ancient China (1983);
    //  Sarah Allan, The Heir and the Sage (1981) and The Shape of the
    //  Turtle (1991).
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

