    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    //  OSSETIAN — Nart saga heroic genealogy
    //  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    //  The Nart sagas (Ossetian: Nartæ Kaddzhytæ; Iron and Digor dialects) are
    //  the national heroic epic of the Iranic-Caucasian Ossetian people,
    //  linguistic and cultural descendants of the Alanic and Sarmatian steppe
    //  nomads who settled the central Caucasus from the 1st millennium BCE
    //  onward. The corpus is structurally parallel to but linguistically and
    //  narratively distinct from the Northwest Caucasian (Adyghe, Abkhaz,
    //  Ubykh) and Northeast Caucasian (Chechen, Ingush) Nart traditions.
    //  The Ossetian recension preserves Iranic-Indo-European mythological
    //  material (Donbettyr the water-deity = Iranic Apam Napāt; the Cosmic
    //  Tree at Wærxæg\'s settlement = the Iranic axis-mundi tree) within a
    //  Caucasian narrative frame.
    //
    //  Genealogical core: Wærxæg (the first Nart, no parents) → twin sons
    //  Akhsar and Akhsartæg (mortal). Akhsartæg marries Dzerassae (demigod,
    //  daughter of the water-deity Donbettyr) → twin sons Uryzmæg and
    //  Khæmyts (quartigod), and posthumously Satana (quartigod, born from
    //  Dzerassae\'s tomb). Khæmyts marries Bytsenon (mortal woman of the
    //  Bytsentæ, a non-human cosmic race not classified as spirit-tier)
    //  → Batraz the steel-hero (scion). Soslan, the second steel-hero,
    //  is excluded from the registry per strict-rule because his
    //  conception (Satana impregnated by a stone heated by a herdsman\'s
    //  desire) places him in the spirit-class-conception forbidden zone.
    //
    //  Sources: Vsevolod Miller, Osetinskie Etyudy (1881-1887, foundational
