    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    //  ARMENIAN — polytheistic pantheon + Khorenatsi mythohistory + Sasna Tsřer
    //  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    //  Three distinct mythological-cultural layers preserved in the Armenian
    //  tradition:
    //
    //  (1) Pre-Christian Iranic-syncretic pantheon (3rd c. BCE - 4th c. CE):
    //  Armenian religion under the Artaxiad and early Arsacid dynasties was
    //  heavily Achaemenid-Parthian-syncretic — the principal deities Aramazd
    //  (= Iranic Ahura Mazda), Anahit (= Anāhitā), Mihr (= Mithra), Vahagn
    //  (= Verethragna), Tir (= scribal-deity reflex), and Astghik
    //  (= astral-feminine paired with Vahagn) preserved Iranian theonyms
    //  with Armenian phonological adaptation. The Vahagn-birth hymn,
    //  preserved by Movses Khorenatsi (Patmutyun Hayots 1.31) quoting
    //  older oral tradition, is one of the oldest surviving fragments of
    //  Armenian poetry — the cosmic-egg birth from heaven-earth-sea-reed
    //  travail. Christianization under Trdat III (301 CE) suppressed the
    //  pantheon-cult institutionally but left substantial ritual-folk
    //  residues into the modern era.
    //
    //  (2) Khorenatsi mytho-historical lineage (5th-c. composition,
    //  encoding earlier oral tradition): Movses Khorenatsi's Patmutyun
    //  Hayots (History of the Armenians) traces the eponymous ancestor
    //  Hayk (traditional dating 2492 BCE per the Battle of Hayots Dzor)
    //  through the Haykazuni dynasty to the historical Arsacid kings.
    //  The lineage Hayk → Aramaneak → Aramayis → Amasya → Gegham → Harma
    //  → Aram → Ara the Beautiful → Anushavan Sosanver covers the legendary
    //  pre-Arsacid period; this registry includes the most-narratively-
    //  developed figures (Hayk, Aramaneak, Aramayis, Aram, Ara, Anushavan)
    //  and elides the chain-fillers (Amasya, Gegham, Harma) noted in
    //  Aram\'s entry.
    //
    //  (3) Sasna Tsřer (Daredevils of Sassoun) heroic epic: medieval
    //  oral-tradition cycle composed 8th-13th c. CE in the Sassoun
    //  highlands; first textually collected by Garegin Srvandzteants in
    //  1873 (Mokats Mirza). The epic\'s four-generation hero-genealogy
    //  Sanasar/Baghdasar (the twin founders, miraculous-conception by
    //  sacred-water from their mother Tsovinar) → Mher the Elder →
    //  David of Sassoun (the central hero) → Mher the Younger (sealed
    //  in the Raven\'s Rock cave waiting for the world\'s end) is the
    //  Armenian national epic.
    //
    //  Sources: (1) Movses Khorenatsi, Patmutyun Hayots / History of the
    //  Armenians (5th c. composition; Thomson translation 1978); the
    //  Khorenatsi text is the foundational chronicle of the Hayk-through-
    //  Anushavan lineage and preserves the Vahagn-birth hymn. (2) Agathangelos,
    //  Patmutyun Hayots (5th c., the conversion-of-Trdat narrative);
    //  Russell, Zoroastrianism in Armenia (1987) for the Iranic-syncretic
    //  pantheon. (3) Garegin Srvandzteants, Grots u Brots / Mokats Mirza
    //  (1873, first published Sasna Tsřer textual collection); Manuk Abeghian
    //  ed., Sasna Tsřer (1936-1951, the Soviet-Armenian academic edition
    //  in 4 volumes); Artin Shalian trans., David of Sassoun: The
    //  Armenian Folk Epic (1964, English translation); Hovhannes Tumanyan,
    //  Davit Sasuntsi (1902, the literary-poetic recasting); Levon Surmelian
    //  trans., Daredevils of Sassoun (1964); James Russell, Yovhannēs
    //  T\'lkurants\'i and the Mediaeval Armenian Lyric Tradition (1987).
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

