    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    //  SLAVIC — polytheistic pantheon + bylina heroic-epic figures
    //  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    //  The Slavic polytheistic pantheon flourished across the East Slavic
    //  (Kievan Rus\'), West Slavic (Polish, Czech, Polabian), and South
    //  Slavic (Serbian, Croatian, Bulgarian) territories until the
    //  988 CE Christianization of Kievan Rus\' under Vladimir the Great
    //  and the parallel Christianization of the West and South Slavic
    //  polities (9th-12th c.). The conversion suppressed institutional
    //  pantheon-cult, with the pantheon-tier deities reaching modern
    //  scholarship through (1) the Primary Chronicle (Povest\' Vremennykh
    //  Let, c. 1113 CE) — which describes Vladimir\'s 980 CE pre-conversion
    //  pantheon-installation at Kiev (Perun, Khors, Dazbog, Stribog,
    //  Simargl, Mokosh) and his 988 CE destruction of the same pantheon;
    //  (2) the Helmold Chronica Slavorum (12th c.) and Saxo Grammaticus
    //  Gesta Danorum (12th c.) on West Slavic-Polabian deities (Svetovid,
    //  Triglav); (3) South Slavic chronicle traditions; and (4) 18th-19th
    //  c. folk-tradition recordings (Afanasyev, Veselovsky) preserving
    //  polytheistic-substrate folk-religious material.
    //
    //  The bylina (East Slavic heroic-epic) is the canonical Slavic
    //  heroic-narrative tradition, composed orally 11th-16th c. and first
    //  textually collected by Kirsha Danilov (1804, Drevnie rossiiskie
    //  stikhotvoreniia) and Pavel Rybnikov (1861-1867, Pesni). The bylina
    //  cycle centers on the bogatyri ("heroic warriors") of Vladimir\'s
    //  Kiev court — Ilya Muromets, Dobrynya Nikitich, and Alyosha Popovich
    //  being the canonical bogatyr trinity. The bylina-heroic-epic figures
    //  are mortal historical-legendary persons with mortal parentage,
    //  strict-pass clean.
    //
    //  Sources: (1) Primary Chronicle / Povest\' Vremennykh Let (c. 1113;
    //  Cross & Sherbowitz-Wetzor trans. 1953); Helmold Chronica Slavorum
    //  (12th c.); Saxo Grammaticus Gesta Danorum (12th c.); Procopius
    //  De Bello Gothico (6th c.) on early Slavic deity-veneration. (2)
    //  A. N. Afanasyev, Poeticheskie vozzreniya slavyan na prirodu /
    //  Poetic Views of the Slavs on Nature (1865-1869) — the foundational
    //  19th-c. comparative-folkloristic work. (3) M. A. Vasmer,
    //  Etimologicheskii slovar\' russkogo yazyka (1953-1958) for theonym
    //  etymology. (4) Roman Jakobson, "Slavic Mythology" in Funk &
    //  Wagnalls Standard Dictionary (1949) and "The Slavic God Veles
    //  and his Indo-European Cognates" (1969). (5) Modern-critical
    //  comprehensive: Mikhail Vasilyev, Yazychestvo Drevnei Rusi (1999);
    //  V. Y. Petrukhin, Mify drevnei Skandinavii i Slavyan (2003).
    //  (6) For bylina: Felix J. Oinas, ed., Heroic Epic and Saga (1978);
    //  Roman Jakobson, "The Vseslav Epos" (1947); James Bailey & Tatyana
    //  Ivanova, An Anthology of Russian Folk Epics (1999, M. E. Sharpe).
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

