        etymology: 'Old East Slavic Мокошь Mokošĭ; etymology contested. Several competing reconstructions: (1) from Proto-Slavic *mok- "wet, moist" (cf. Russian мокрый mokryj "wet"; Slovenian močiti "to moisten"), matching the "Moist Mother Earth" (Mat\' Syra Zemlya) folk-epithet — the most-widely-accepted etymology; (2) from a borrowing from Finno-Ugric Mok\'š\'a, the ethnonym of the Mordvin people; (3) from a deeper Indo-European root. The first reading is the consensus-scholarly position.',
