    //  DINÉ (Navajo) — Diné Bahaneʼ creator + Hero Twin
    //  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    //  The Diné Bahaneʼ ("Story of the People") is the foundational Diné
    //  cosmological-religious narrative tradition. The Four Worlds emergence
    //  cosmogony establishes the foundational primordial-creator pair First
    //  Man (Áłtsé Hastiin) and First Woman (Áłtsé Asdzą́ą́), the emergence
    //  of the Diné into the present Fourth (or Fifth, per recension) World,
    //  and the formation of Asdzą́ą́ Nádleehé / Changing Woman from a
    //  cosmic-egg discovered on Gobernador Knob (Ch\'óol\'į́\'í). The Hero
    //  Twins (Naayééʼ Neizghání / Monster Slayer and Tó Bájíshchíní /
    //  Born for Water) are conceived by Changing Woman through the Sun
    //  (Jóhonaaʼéí) and Water, undertaking the foundational monster-
    //  slaying cycle that cleared the Diné homeland of the alien-monsters
    //  (Naayééʼ) preventing safe Diné occupation.
    //
    //  Sources: Paul Zolbrod, Diné Bahaneʼ: The Navajo Creation Story
    //  (1984, University of New Mexico Press); Berard Haile, Origin Legend
    //  of the Navaho Enemy Way (1938, Yale University Publications in
    //  Anthropology); Washington Matthews, Navaho Legends (1897); Aileen
    //  O\'Bryan, Navajo Indian Myths (1956, Smithsonian); Karl W. Luckert,
    //  The Navajo Hunter Tradition (1975); Sam Gill, Songs of Life: An
    //  Introduction to Navajo Religious Culture (1979). Community-led:
    //  Diné College Diné Studies Department publications.
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

