    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    //  MAYA — K'iche' Popol Vuh narrative cluster
    //  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    //  The K'iche' Maya council-book preserves the most complete extant
    //  Mesoamerican mythological corpus. The Hero Twins cycle (Books I-IV)
    //  centers on three generations: the creator-grandparents Xpiacoc and
    //  Xmucane; their twin sons Hun Hunahpu and Vucub Hunahpu; and the
    //  grandsons Hunahpu and Xbalanque (the Hero Twins) by Xquic, daughter
    //  of the Xibalba lord Cuchumaquic. The narrative anchors the K'iche'
    //  royal lineages of the late Postclassic (Cawek, Nihaib, Ahau-Quiché)
    //  in deity-genealogical descent, functioning as dynastic charter for
    //  the Q'umarkaj/Utatlán polity until its conquest in 1524.
    //
    //  Iconographic continuity: the Classic Maya Maize God (Hun Nal Ye, God
    //  E in Schellhas's typology) is widely identified as the Classic-period
    //  reflex of Hun Hunahpu, and the Hero Twins narrative is depicted on
    //  Late Preclassic Izapa Stelae 5/10/25 (c. 400 BCE - 100 CE) and
