    //  The Mixtec dynastic codices (Codex Vindobonensis = Yuta Tnoho; Codex
    //  Zouche-Nuttall = Tonindeye; Codex Bodley = Ñuu Tnoo–Ndisi Nuu; Codex
    //  Colombino-Becker; Codex Selden = Añute) are the most extensive non-
    //  Maya Mesoamerican royal-genealogical corpus, encoding pre-Conquest
    //  Mixteca-Alta dynasties through painted screen-fold deerskin and
    //  bark-paper books with a Mixtec-language glyphic system distinct from
    //  the Aztec/Mexica Nahuatl tradition. The two narrative anchors of the
    //  corpus are: (1) the Apoala sacred-tree emergence cosmogony, in which
    //  the creator pair Lord 1 Deer and Lady 1 Deer emerge from the cleft
    //  tree at Yuta Tnoho ("River of Lineages") and engender the Mixtec
    //  pantheon-tier figures who in turn engender the founder-dynasties of
    //  the Mixteca-Alta polities; and (2) the dynastic biography of Lord 8
    //  Deer Jaguar Claw of Tilantongo (1063-1115 CE), the most-fully-
    //  documented historical-mythological figure in pre-Conquest Mexico.
    //
    //  Naming convention: Mixtec personal names combine a calendar-name
    //  (day-sign + numerical coefficient from the 260-day count) with a
    //  personal-epithet. The registry preserves the conventional English
    //  rendering ("Lord 8 Deer Jaguar Claw" = Iya Nacuaa Teyusi Ñaña) while
    //  giving Mixtec-language transliteration where attested.
    //
    //  Sources: Codex Vindobonensis Mexicanus I (Codex Yuta Tnoho), pre-
    //  Conquest, Österreichische Nationalbibliothek; Codex Zouche-Nuttall
    //  (Codex Tonindeye), pre-Conquest, British Museum; Codex Bodley, pre-
    //  Conquest, Bodleian Library Oxford; Codex Colombino-Becker, pre-
    //  Conquest, fragmented across Mexico City and Berlin; Codex Selden
    //  (Codex Añute), post-Conquest c. 1556-1560, Bodleian Library Oxford.
    //  Modern decipherment: Alfonso Caso, Reyes y Reinos de la Mixteca
    //  (1977-1979); Maarten Jansen and Aurora Pérez Jiménez, Encounter with
    //  the Plumed Serpent (2007); John M. D. Pohl, The Politics of
    //  Symbolism in the Mixtec Codices (1994); Robert Lloyd Williams,
    //  The Complete Codex Zouche-Nuttall (2013); Bruce E. Byland and
    //  John M. D. Pohl, In the Realm of 8 Deer (1994). Genealogical-
    //  chronological reconstruction by Caso (1949-1977) provides the
    //  conventional Western dating for the Tilantongo dynastic cluster.
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

