    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    //  INCA — imperial state-cult founders + Sapa Inca dynasty
    //  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    //  Tahuantinsuyu ("the Four-Quarters United") — the largest pre-Columbian
    //  empire of the Americas — was framed by an explicit theogony-of-state:
    //  the Sapa Inca was sapan inka punchaupaq churi, "the unique Inca, son
    //  of the Sun." The state cult of Inti at the Coricancha temple in Cuzco,
    //  the panaca system whereby each deceased Sapa Inca's mummy and
    //  household continued as a corporate landowning lineage, the ceque
    //  system of 41 sight-lines radiating from Coricancha encoding ancestor-
    //  shrine geography, and the annual Inti Raymi solstice festival together
    //  ratified the genealogical continuity from the Pacaritambo emergence
    //  to the reigning emperor. The chronicle tradition (Cieza de León 1553,
    //  Betanzos 1551, Sarmiento de Gamboa 1572, Garcilaso de la Vega 1609,
    //  Guaman Poma c. 1615) records the dynastic line of nine pre-Conquest
    //  Sapa Incas from the founder Manco Cápac through Pachacuti.
    //
    //  Authoring choices: Inti as paternal deity for all eight Pacaritambo
    //  founders (Garcilaso variant), with unnamed mortal mother per the
    //  patrilineal Quechua convention — yields clean demigod-class founders.
    //  Mama Killa (Moon goddess, paired consort of Inti in Garcilaso's
    //  account) is included as a freestanding pantheon-tier deity. Variants
    //  noted in entry-internal documentation: Sarmiento makes Manco Cápac
    //  son of Viracocha; Cieza preserves the Pacaritambo emergence-from-cave
    //  narrative without explicit divine paternity.
    //
    //  Sources: Pedro Cieza de León, Crónica del Perú Part II (1553);
    //  Juan de Betanzos, Suma y Narración de los Incas (1551); Pedro
    //  Sarmiento de Gamboa, Historia Índica (1572, Toledo-commissioned);
    //  Inca Garcilaso de la Vega, Comentarios Reales de los Incas (1609);
    //  Felipe Guaman Poma de Ayala, El Primer Nueva Corónica y Buen
    //  Gobierno (c. 1615). Modern: Rostworowski, Historia del Tahuantinsuyu
    //  (1988); Julien, Reading Inca History (2000); D'Altroy, The Incas (2002).
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

