      parentIds: ['inca_viracocha_inca'],
      parentRoles: { inca_viracocha_inca: 'paternal' },
      temporal: { era: 'imperial' },
      lifecycle: [
        { typeStatus: 'scion', era: 'pre-imperial', eraOrdering: 0, startEvent: 'birth-at-Cuzco-c-1400', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Sarmiento Ch. 24; Betanzos Pt. I Ch. 6' }], notes: 'Born at Cuzco; given the pre-regnal name Cusi Yupanqui ("Joy / Esteemed-Honored"). Conventionally c. 1400 CE; not the designated heir-apparent (that role went to his elder brother Inca Urco).' },
        { typeStatus: 'scion', era: 'pre-imperial', eraOrdering: 1, startEvent: 'defense-of-Cuzco-against-Chanka-invasion-1438', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Sarmiento Ch. 26-27; Betanzos Pt. I Ch. 7-8; Cieza Pt. II Ch. 44-46' }], notes: 'When the Chanka confederacy under Astoy-Huaraca and Tomay-Huaraca invaded Cuzco c. 1438, Cusi Yupanqui — alone among the Inca royals — refused to flee. Defended Cuzco with a small force; per Betanzos\'s panaca-internal account, the Inca creator-deity Viracocha appeared to him in a dream and promised victory; per Sarmiento, the very stones of Cuzco transformed into warriors (purun auca, "ferocious warriors") to fight alongside him. Defeated the Chankas at the battle of Yawarpampa ("plain of blood"), saving Cuzco.' },
        { typeStatus: 'scion', vitalStatus: 'sapa-inca-acclaimed', era: 'imperial', eraOrdering: 0, startEvent: 'acclamation-as-Sapa-Inca-1438', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Sarmiento Ch. 27-28; Betanzos Pt. I Ch. 17-18' }], notes: 'Acclaimed Sapa Inca in his father\'s place by the panacas of Cuzco; took the regnal name Pachakuti Yupanki ("World-Overturner Honored One"), explicitly framing his accession as a cosmic-pivot event.' },
        { typeStatus: 'scion', vitalStatus: 'sapa-inca-reigning', era: 'imperial', eraOrdering: 1, startEvent: 'imperial-expansion-and-state-formation', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Sarmiento Ch. 28-46; Betanzos Pt. I Ch. 18-32; Cieza Pt. II Ch. 47-58' }], notes: 'Reigned c. 1438-1471. Conducted the foundational imperial expansion of Tahuantinsuyu, conquering the Soras, Lupacas, Collas (around Lake Titicaca), Chinchas (coastal), and the Chimú kingdom of the north coast. Reorganized Cuzco architecturally (rebuilt the Coricancha in cut-stone masonry, planned the city in puma-shape per legend); established the formal panaca system, the ceque sight-line ritual geography, the mit\'a labor-rotation tax, the qhapaq ñan road network, and the imperial-state quipu accounting bureaucracy. Possibly initiated the construction of Machu Picchu as a royal estate.' },
        { typeStatus: 'scion', era: 'imperial', eraOrdering: 2, startEvent: 'co-rule-and-succession-planning', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Sarmiento Ch. 47; Cobo Bk. XII Ch. 14' }], notes: 'Late in his reign, associated his son Túpac Inka Yupanki in co-rule and military command; Túpac Inka conducted further northern expansion to Quito while Pachacuti administered Cuzco.' },
        { vitalStatus: 'dead', era: 'imperial', eraOrdering: 3, startEvent: 'death-c-1471', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Sarmiento Ch. 47; Betanzos Pt. I Ch. 32' }], notes: 'Died at Cuzco c. 1471. Buried with elaborate state mourning; his mummy resided in the Coricancha and was a focal object of imperial-state veneration through the conquest. Founded the Hatun Ayllu / Iñaqa Panaca, the most-prestigious of the imperial-period panacas.' },
      ],
