    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    //  AKAN — Nyame-Asase Yaa-Anansi pantheon + Asante imperial dynasty
    //  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    //  The Akan peoples (Ashanti, Fante, Akyem, Akwamu, Brong, Bono, Akuapem)
    //  of modern Ghana and adjacent Côte d\'Ivoire constitute one of the most-
    //  cohesive cultural-linguistic complexes of West Africa, sharing the
    //  Twi-Fante language family, matrilineal-mogya-and-patrilineal-ntoro
    //  dual-descent kinship structure, and the foundational pantheon of
    //  Nyame (Sky-God supreme being), Asase Yaa (Earth-Mother), and the
    //  hierarchically-arranged abosom (lesser deities) and ancestor spirits.
    //
    //  Pantheon-tier: Nyame is the Sky-God supreme being, structurally
    //  parallel to but theologically distinct from the Yoruba Olodumare
    //  and the Igbo Chukwu — the deistic-remote creator who delegates
    //  active intervention to the abosom. Asase Yaa (literally "Earth-
    //  Thursday-Lady," from Asase + Yaa "Thursday-born female") is the
    //  Earth-Mother fertility-and-justice goddess. Anansi (Kwaku Anansi,
    //  "Anansi-Wednesday-male") is the trickster-spider-figure son of
    //  Nyame and Asase Yaa per the canonical Asante recension; the Anansi-
    //  cycle is the most-narratively-developed tradition of the Akan
    //  pantheon and was transmitted through the Atlantic slave trade to
    //  the Caribbean (the Anancy stories of Jamaica and elsewhere).
    //
    //  Asante imperial dynasty: The Asante Empire (Asanteman) was founded
    //  in 1675-1701 by the matrilineal-uncle-and-nephew pair Obiri Yeboa
    //  (Kwaman/Kumasi chief) and Osei Tutu I (Asantehene), in conjunction
    //  with the priest-counselor Komfo Anokye (Okomfo Anokye), who in 1701
    //  conjured the Sika Dwa Kofi (Golden Stool) down from heaven —
    //  containing the soul of the Asante nation — at the foundational
    //  council of Kumasi. Akan succession is matrilineal: the Asantehene
    //  is succeeded by the sister\'s son, not the son. The registry\'s
    //  biological-parent-only model does not directly encode matrilineal
    //  succession; for political-successor figures (Osei Tutu, Opoku
    //  Ware, Yaa Asantewaa, Prempeh I, Prempeh II), parentIds are left
    //  empty with the matrilineal-uncle succession documented in entry
    //  notes. Anansi is the only registered parent-child link in the
    //  Akan cluster.
    //
    //  Sources: (1) Pantheon — R. S. Rattray, Ashanti (1923) and
    //  Religion and Art in Ashanti (1927) — the foundational ethnographic
    //  surveys; Eva Meyerowitz, The Sacred State of the Akan (1951) and
    //  The Divine Kingship in Ghana and Ancient Egypt (1960); Kwesi Yankah,
    //  Speaking for the Chief (1995); Peggy Appiah, Anansi the Spider
    //  (1972, English-language Anansi-cycle compilation). (2) Imperial
    //  history — Ivor Wilks, Asante in the Nineteenth Century (1975) and
    //  Forests of Gold (1993); J. K. Fynn, Asante and Its Neighbours
    //  (1971); T. C. McCaskie, State and Society in Pre-Colonial Asante
    //  (1995); A. A. Boahen, Yaa Asantewaa and the Asante-British War of
    //  1900-1 (2003). (3) Primary documents — Asantehene Court archives;
    //  T. Edward Bowdich, Mission from Cape Coast Castle to Ashantee (1819);
    //  Joseph Dupuis, Journal of a Residence in Ashantee (1824); Ramseyer
    //  & Kühne missionary captivity narrative (1875).
    // ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

