    // ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    // PHASE 13 — Polynesian Tāwhaki/Wahieroa/Rata cycle. The canonical
    // pan-Polynesian heroic genealogy preserved in Maori (Grey 1855, White
    // 1887-1890, Tregear 1891, Best 1924), Hawaiian (Fornander 1878), and
    // Tahitian recensions: Whaitiri (cannibalistic sky-goddess) × Kaitangata
    // (mortal man) → Hemā (demigod) → Tāwhaki (quartigod, the canonical
    // sky-climber hero, structurally parallel to Cú Chulainn and Heracles)
    // → Wahieroa (scion, killed by Matuku-takotako) → Rata (mortal-floor,
    // the canoe-builder avenger). Per Cole-Jensen 1961 and Fornander 1878
    // pp. 190-191, the genealogy from Tāwhaki through Rata is shared
    // between Hawaiian and Maori traditions in the same order — proof that
    // the genealogy existed in the Tahitian homeland before Polynesian
    // dispersal. The existing registry has Makeatutara (deity), Tama-nui-
    // ki-te-rangi (deity), Taranga (mortal), and Māui (demigod) for the
    // separate Maori Māui-cycle; the Tāwhaki cycle is parallel-but-distinct.
    // ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

