      lifecycle: [
        { typeStatus: 'quartigod', startEvent: 'birth-as-Pelias-Anaxibia-only-son', era: 'heroic-age', eraOrdering: 0, sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Apollod. 1.9.10' }], notes: 'Son of Pelias by Anaxibia (daughter of Bias) per Apollodorus 1.9.10; the Phylomache variant per "according to some" is the alternative-maternity reading. Quartigod-tier through paternal Poseidon-line via Pelias. Brother of the Peliades — Pisidice, Pelopia, Hippothoe, and Alcestis.' },
        { typeStatus: 'quartigod', startEvent: 'Argonautic-expedition-with-Jason', era: 'heroic-age', eraOrdering: 1, sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Apollod. 1.9.16; Apoll. Rhod. Argon. 1.224 ff.; Pind. Nem. 4.65; Hyg. Fab. 14' }], notes: 'Sailed with Jason on the Argo per the canonical-Argonautic catalogue — joining the expedition his father Pelias had hoped would kill Jason. Per Valerius Flaccus Argonautica 1, Jason convinced his cousin Acastus to join the expedition specifically to spite Pelias. Acastus\'s role in the voyage was canonically inconsequential per the dominant tradition.' },
        { typeStatus: 'quartigod', startEvent: 'Calydonian-Boar-Hunt-participation', era: 'heroic-age', eraOrdering: 2, sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Ovid Met. 8.305 ff.; Hyg. Fab. 173' }], notes: 'Participant in the Calydonian Boar Hunt per Ovid and Hyginus.' },
        { typeStatus: 'quartigod', vitalStatus: 'king-of-Iolcus', era: 'heroic-age', eraOrdering: 3, startEvent: 'accession-to-Iolcian-kingship-after-Medea-trick-killing-of-Pelias', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Apollod. 1.9.27; Pind. Nem. 4.54-65' }], notes: 'After Medea tricked the Peliades into dismembering Pelias, buried his father; expelled Jason and Medea from Iolcus (and per Pausanias 8.11.3 also his murderous sisters); instituted the canonical-Greek funeral games for Pelias — among the largest in the heroic-age tradition, attended by most of the surviving Argonauts and Calydonian-Boar hunters.' },
        { typeStatus: 'quartigod', startEvent: 'purification-of-Peleus-and-Astydameia-betrayal', era: 'heroic-age', eraOrdering: 4, sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Apollod. 3.13.2-3; Pind. Nem. 4.54-65; Hes. fr. 209 M-W' }], notes: 'Purified Peleus of the accidental killing of Eurytion at the Calydonian Boar Hunt. While Peleus stayed as guest at Iolcus, Acastus\'s wife Astydameia (also called Hippolyte daughter of Cretheus per Apollod. 3.13.3, distinct from the Amazon) fell in love with Peleus and was rejected; she falsely accused him of attempted rape. Acastus, unwilling to kill the man he had purified, took Peleus hunting on Pelion, hid his sword while he slept, and abandoned him to be killed by centaurs.' },
        { vitalStatus: 'deceased', era: 'heroic-age', eraOrdering: 5, startEvent: 'death-by-Peleus-Iason-and-Dioscuri-sack-of-Iolcus', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Apollod. 3.13.7; Eur. Tro. (allusion); Lycophron Alex. 175' }], notes: 'Survived by Chiron (the centaur who restored his sword to Peleus), Peleus returned with Jason and the Dioscuri to sack Iolcus. Killed Astydameia and dismembered her — per the canonical Apollodorus 3.13.7 narrative, Peleus marched his army between the pieces of her body. Apollodorus is silent on Acastus\'s own death; some accounts (Hesiod fr. 209 M-W; the post-Apollodoran scholiastic tradition) have Peleus kill Acastus also. His son Thessalus succeeded him and gave his name to Thessaly per the canonical eponymic-tradition.' },
      ],
      domains: [{ id: 'Argonaut' }, { id: 'king-of-Iolcus' }, { id: 'host-of-Pelias-funeral-games' }, { id: 'purifier-of-Peleus' }],
