      linguistic: {
        etymology: 'Welsh Llŷr; cognate with Irish Lir / Ler (Old Irish ler "sea"). The Irish Lir is a sea-deity (father of Manannán mac Lir); the Welsh Llŷr is rationalized in the medieval Mabinogion recension into a mortal-king-figure. The epithet Llediaith ("Half-Speech," from Welsh hanner "half" + iaith "language") preserves alien-or-foreign-origin status, possibly reflecting the cognate-Irish-deity-figure\'s reduction in the Welsh tradition.',
        languageFamily: 'Indo-European (Insular Celtic, Brittonic-Welsh)',
      },
      sources: [
        { claim: 'existence', citations: [
          { kind: 'primary', reference: 'Pedeir Keinc y Mabinogi — Second Branch (Branwen ferch Llŷr)' },
          { kind: 'primary', reference: 'Trioedd Ynys Prydein (Welsh Triads), No. 8 and elsewhere' },
        ], weight: 'primary' },
      ],
      notes: 'Father of the Branch-2 trio (Bendigeidfran, Branwen, Manawydan) by Penarddun; rationalized king-figure of the Welsh Mabinogion tradition. The epithet Llediaith ("Half-Speech") preserves alien-or-foreign-origin status, possibly reflecting the cognate-Irish-Lir-deity figure\'s reduction in the Welsh tradition into a mortal-king-class figure. The registry adopts the medieval-Welsh rationalized reading, treating Llŷr as mortal-class. By the time of the Branch-2 narrative he is dead; his son Bendigeidfran reigns as king of Britain. The Llŷr-cognate Irish sea-deity Lir is preserved in Irish tradition through his son Manannán mac Lir; the Welsh equivalent Manawydan fab Llŷr appears in Branch 2 and Branch 3 of the Mabinogi as the central figure of the Third Branch.',
