      lifecycle: [
        { typeStatus: 'mortal', era: 'mabinogion-mythological', eraOrdering: 0, sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Mabinogion Second Branch' }], notes: 'Son of Penarddun by Eurosswydd (her second husband); half-brother of Bendigeidfran, Branwen, and Manawydan. Twin brother of Nisien — but where Nisien is described as wholly peace-loving, Efnisien is described as wholly conflict-provoking, the two twins functioning as a foundational good/evil dyad in the Branch-2 narrative.' },
        { typeStatus: 'mortal', era: 'mabinogion-mythological', eraOrdering: 1, startEvent: 'maiming-of-Matholwch-horses', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Mabinogion Second Branch' }], notes: 'Outraged at not having been consulted in his half-sister Branwen\'s marriage to Matholwch, maimed Matholwch\'s horses (cutting their lips, ears, eyebrows, and tails to the bone). The maiming was the foundational provocation that initiated the chain of events leading to the catastrophic Welsh-Irish war.' },
        { typeStatus: 'mortal', era: 'mabinogion-mythological', eraOrdering: 2, startEvent: 'killing-of-Gwern', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Mabinogion Second Branch' }], notes: 'During the peace-feast at Matholwch\'s court at the Welsh-arrival, took his nephew Gwern (Branwen\'s son by Matholwch) by the feet and threw him into the fire. The Gwern-killing was the immediate trigger of the open Welsh-Irish war that destroyed both polities.' },
        { vitalStatus: 'dead', era: 'mabinogion-mythological', eraOrdering: 3, startEvent: 'self-sacrifice-in-Cauldron-of-Rebirth', sources: [{ kind: 'primary', reference: 'Mabinogion Second Branch' }], notes: 'During the Welsh-Irish war, when the Irish were resurrecting their slain warriors through the Cauldron of Rebirth (Bendigeidfran\'s gift to Matholwch), hid himself among the slain Irish dead and was placed in the cauldron; once inside, stretched himself with such force that his heart broke and the cauldron shattered — destroying the Irish capacity for resurrection but also killing himself. The self-sacrificial cauldron-shattering is the most-redemptive act in the Branch-2 narrative.' },
      ],
